Very recently, many works have been focused on the analysis of mathematical models described by ordinary differential equations with control effects [30–33]. Particularly, the state-dependent impulsive control strategies are applied widely to the prevention of spread of infectious disease due to its economic, high efficiency, and feasibility nature. This idea can be found in many other areas like agricultural production and fishery industry; where the control measures, such as catching, poisoning, releasing the natural enemy, and harvesting, are taken only when the number of population reaches an economic threshold value. Following this idea, the dynamic behaviors of population, epidemic and language models with state-dependent impulsive effects are considered, and the existence and stability of positive periodic solution by the Poincaré map, properties of the Lambert \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
